  <div class="hero-label">What's at stake — Health</div>
  <h1 class="hero-title">Four EDs.<br>One Island.</h1>
  <p class="hero-subtitle">PEI's emergency health system serves 182,000 people across four hospital emergency departments — with no trauma centre, limited specialist coverage, and 33,000 patients without a family doctor.</p>
  <hr class="hero-rule">

  <div class="fact-strip">
    <div class="fact-card">
      <div class="fact-num">4</div>
      <div class="fact-label">emergency departments serving the entire province</div>
    </div>
    <div class="fact-card">
      <div class="fact-num">33,000</div>
      <div class="fact-label">Islanders without a family doctor or nurse practitioner</div>
    </div>
    <div class="fact-card">
      <div class="fact-num">&gt;10 hrs</div>
      <div class="fact-label">Level 3 (Urgent) wait time at QEH recorded April 5, 2026</div>
    </div>
    <div class="fact-card">
      <div class="fact-num">60</div>
      <div class="fact-label">total patients in QEH emergency on that same Sunday morning</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <h2 class="section-title">The four hospitals</h2>
    <div class="hospital-grid">
      <div class="hospital-card">
        <div class="hospital-name">Queen Elizabeth Hospital</div>
        <div class="hospital-short">QEH · Charlottetown</div>
        <div class="hospital-detail">PEI's only acute care referral centre. Largest ED, most specialist coverage. Serves Charlottetown and surrounding Queens County — roughly 50% of the island's population.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="hospital-card">
        <div class="hospital-name">Prince County Hospital</div>
        <div class="hospital-short">PCH · Summerside</div>
        <div class="hospital-detail">Second-largest facility. Serves Prince County (western PEI). Full ED, some specialist coverage, surgical services. Roughly 35% of island population catchment.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="hospital-card">
        <div class="hospital-name">Western Hospital</div>
        <div class="hospital-short">WH · Alberton</div>
        <div class="hospital-detail">Serves western Prince County. Small ED, limited specialist access. Complex cases transferred to PCH or QEH. Essential for rural western communities.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="hospital-card">
        <div class="hospital-name">Kings County Memorial</div>
        <div class="hospital-short">KCMH · Montague</div>
        <div class="hospital-detail">Serves Kings County (eastern PEI). ED closes periodically due to staffing — when closed, nearest alternative is QEH, 50+ km away. Most vulnerable ED on the island.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="section-body" style="margin-top:1rem;">
      <p>PEI has no Level 1 trauma centre. Patients requiring major trauma care, neurosurgery, or cardiac intervention are typically air-transported to Halifax (IWK/QEII) or Moncton. This creates a fundamental constraint: for time-sensitive conditions, geography is destiny.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <h2 class="section-title">Reading the ED wait time data</h2>
    <div class="section-body">
      <p>Health PEI publishes live emergency department wait times through the GPEI portal. The data is updated regularly and shows patients by triage level — the Canadian Triage and Acuity Scale (CTAS), which classifies every ED patient from Level 1 (immediately life-threatening) through Level 5 (non-urgent).</p>
      <p>The dashboard displays <strong>total patients in the ED</strong> and the <strong>Level 3 (Urgent) wait time</strong> as the primary signal, because Level 3 represents the largest share of patients in a functioning ED and its wait time is the most sensitive indicator of overall ED pressure.</p>
    </div>
    <table class="triage-table">
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Level</th><th>Name</th><th>Target response</th><th>Examples</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td class="l1">L1</td><td>Resuscitation</td><td>Immediate</td><td>Cardiac arrest, major trauma</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="l2">L2</td><td>Emergent (Most Urgent)</td><td>15 minutes</td><td>Chest pain, stroke symptoms, severe pain</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="l3">L3</td><td>Urgent</td><td>30 minutes</td><td>Moderate pain, infection, non-severe injury</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="l4">L4</td><td>Less Urgent</td><td>60 minutes</td><td>Minor injury, earache, minor illness</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="l5">L5</td><td>Non-Urgent</td><td>120 minutes</td><td>Prescription renewal, minor wound check</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <div class="section-body" style="margin-top:1rem;">
      <p>When Level 3 wait times exceed 4–6 hours at QEH, it is typically a sign that the ED is experiencing significant crowding — often due to <strong>admitted patients boarding in the ED</strong> (patients who have been admitted to hospital but cannot access an inpatient bed) rather than the volume of walk-in patients per se. This is a system-wide capacity issue, not an ED design issue.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <h2 class="section-title">The 33,000 without a doctor</h2>
    <div class="section-body">
      <p>PEI's patient registry — maintained by Health PEI — tracks Islanders who do not have an attached family physician or nurse practitioner. As of early 2026, that number stands at approximately <strong>33,000 people</strong>, roughly 18% of the island's population.</p>
      <p>This figure is directly connected to ED pressure. Patients without primary care access have no option but the emergency department for conditions that would otherwise be managed in a community clinic — infections, chronic disease management, prescription renewals, minor injuries. These patients do not require emergency care by CTAS definition, but they have nowhere else to go.</p>
      <p>Health PEI's "medical homes" program and the provincial attachment strategy have reduced the unattached count from a peak above 40,000, but progress has slowed as recruitment competes with national shortages and PEI's cost-of-living increases make the island less attractive to incoming physicians relative to urban centres.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <h2 class="section-title">KCMH — the fragile ED</h2>
    <div class="section-body">
      <p>Kings County Memorial Hospital's emergency department operates on a staffing model that is vulnerable to coverage gaps. When physician or nursing coverage cannot be arranged, the ED closes — sometimes with short notice, sometimes overnight or over a weekend. When this happens, residents of eastern PEI face a drive of 50 kilometres or more to QEH in Charlottetown.</p>
      <p>The dashboard detects KCMH closures in real time. When the GPEI portal returns a closure notice rather than wait time data, the dashboard displays a red alert. On April 5, 2026 — the day this system was first connected — KCMH was indeed closed, with a message indicating it would reopen Monday at 8 AM. This is not an anomaly; it is an operational reality that the eastern PEI community lives with.</p>
      <p>For a region with an aging population and significant rates of chronic disease, an ED that closes on weekends is a meaningful safety risk. Calling 911 remains the appropriate response for life-threatening emergencies regardless of local ED status — but for the many conditions that sit between "urgent" and "life-threatening," a closed KCMH forces a difficult calculation.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <h2 class="section-title">Dashboard thresholds explained</h2>
    <table class="threshold-table">
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Indicator</th><th>Status</th><th>Threshold</th><th>What it means</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>QEH ED — Total patients</td>
          <td><span class="pill pill-alert">ALERT</span></td>
          <td>&gt;60 patients</td>
          <td>High capacity — extended waits expected across all levels</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>QEH ED — Total patients</td>
          <td><span class="pill pill-warn">WARN</span></td>
          <td>40–60 patients</td>
          <td>Busy ED — above-average waits likely</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>QEH ED — Total patients</td>
          <td><span class="pill pill-ok">OK</span></td>
          <td>&lt;40 patients</td>
          <td>Normal operating conditions</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>QEH Level 3 wait time</td>
          <td><span class="pill pill-alert">ALERT</span></td>
          <td>&gt;10 hours</td>
          <td>Severe crowding — systemic bed access issue likely</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>QEH Level 3 wait time</td>
          <td><span class="pill pill-warn">WARN</span></td>
          <td>4–10 hours</td>
          <td>Extended wait — consider urgent care alternatives for non-emergency</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>KCMH ED status</td>
          <td><span class="pill pill-alert">ALERT</span></td>
          <td>Closed</td>
          <td>Eastern PEI has no local emergency department — nearest is QEH (50+ km)</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>PCH / WH ED</td>
          <td><span class="pill pill-warn">WARN</span></td>
          <td>&gt;40 patients or Level 3 &gt;4 hrs</td>
          <td>Above normal pressure for regional facility</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

